{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 12:14:52.586507", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — multi-tier Clos (fat-tree) EBGP lab\n\nScope and approach\n- Goal: determine whether the network shows abnormal behaviour, localize the fault(s) and identify likely root cause(s).\n- Methods used: reachability sweeps, targeted pings from hosts and routers, inspection of host & router L3 config and kernel neighbor state, FRR/BGP route inspection.\n- Tools: ping tests, get_host_net_config, ip neigh, show BGP outputs captured from FRR (provided).\n\nExecutive summary / overall health\n- The EBGP control plane looks healthy: FRR BGP tables on super-spine, spines and leaves show the expected /24 host subnets and inter-router /31s; routes for all 10.* /24 prefixes are present across routers (multipath/ECMP info visible).\n- Most host-to-host connectivity across the fabric works (many PCs successfully pinged remote prefixes in the reachability sweep).\n- Exception / anomaly: mutual connectivity failure between pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2/24) and pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2/24). Both directions show 100% loss. The problem localizes to the two leaf edges and/or the L2 between each PC and its leaf router.\n\nEvidence / observations (relevant excerpts)\n1) Direct ping tests between the two PCs\n- From pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1:\n  - ping from pc_0_0 to 10.0.1.2: 100% packet loss (attempted with -W 1).\n  - Tool timeout occurred on one attempt.\n- From pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0:\n  - ping from pc_0_1 to 10.0.0.2: 100% packet loss.\n\n2) Router-to-host pings (leaf routers to the opposite host)\n- leaf_router_0_0 -> 10.0.1.2: ping reports 100% loss (leaf_router_0_0 could not reach pc_0_1).\n- leaf_router_0_1 -> 10.0.0.2: ping reports 100% loss (leaf_router_0_1 could not reach pc_0_0).\n  - This indicates the problem is visible at the leaf routers (not just the hosts).\n\n3) Host and leaf-router interface configuration\n- pc_0_0:\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.0.2/24, default via 10.0.0.1\n  - ifconfig shows the interface UP; small packet counts (RX 1, TX 5).\n- pc_0_1:\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.1.2/24, default via 10.0.1.1\n  - interface UP; small packet counts.\n- leaf_router_0_0:\n  - eth8: inet 10.0.0.1/24 (this is the router's address for the 10.0.0.0/24)\n  - other ethX interfaces show expected 172.16.x/31 addresses to spines.\n  - ip route contains 10.0.0.0/24 dev eth8 proto kernel scope link src 10.0.0.1\n  - ip route also contains an unexpected/interesting entry: \"blackhole 10.0.0.0/30 proto static metric 20\" at top of the route listing (see note below).\n- leaf_router_0_1:\n  - eth8: inet 10.0.1.1/24; routes present for all prefixes.\n\n4) ARP / neighbor state on leaf_router_0_0\n- ip neigh show on leaf_router_0_0 lists neighbors for the inter-router 172.16.1.x links only. There is no ARP/neighbor entry for 10.0.0.2 (pc_0_0).\n  - This indicates the leaf router has not learned the host’s MAC via ARP (no L2 adjacency seen by the router for its directly-connected host).\n\n5) BGP / routing plane\n- FRR BGP tables (leafs/spines/super-spine) show the expected /24s (including 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24) and next-hops — routes for all 10.* prefixes are present. The control-plane distribution is consistent; no missing /24s were observed.\n\nAnomalies and immediate conclusions\n- Primary anomaly: mutual connectivity failure between pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2) and pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2). Both hosts cannot ping each other; their leaf routers cannot ping the opposite host either.\n- Secondary anomaly: on leaf_router_0_0, there is no ARP entry for the local host (10.0.0.2) even though the router has 10.0.0.1/24 configured and the PC interface is up. That shows an L2 adjacency problem between pc_0_0 and its leaf.\n- The BGP control plane and IGP connectivity between routers appear healthy and complete — the problem is not a FIB/routing propagation issue for the /24 prefixes (those prefixes are visible across the fabric).\n\nLocalization (most likely affected components / links)\n- leaf_router_0_0 and the L2 link to pc_0_0 (10.0.0.1 <-> 10.0.0.2).\n- leaf_router_0_1 and the L2 link to pc_0_1 (10.0.1.1 <-> 10.0.1.2).\n- pc_0_0 and pc_0_1 themselves (end host NIC configurations) — their IPs and default routes are configured but they are not being learned by their leaf routers via ARP in at least one case.\n- The larger fabric (spines, super-spine, BGP) is unlikely to be the root cause because their route tables include the affected /24 prefixes and other cross-pod host reachability is working.\n\nLikely root-cause hypotheses (ranked)\n1) Local L2 adjacency failure between each host and its leaf (most likely)\n   - Evidence: leaf_router_0_0 has no ARP entry for 10.0.0.2; leaf_router_0_0 eth8 is configured 10.0.0.1/24; pc_0_0 eth0 is configured 10.0.0.2/24 but kernel neighbor is missing and pings from leaf to pc fail.\n   - This could be caused by a cabling/mapping mismatch in the topology (host attached to a different interface than the one configured), the host NIC being in a wrong namespace, or a down/miswired virtual link.\n\n2) Host NIC misconfiguration / namespace mismatch\n   - Evidence: leaf_router_0_0 eth8 is 10.0.0.1, but in the topology leaf_router_0_0 is documented as connecting to pc_0_0 on eth2. If physical/namespace interface mapping is inconsistent, the router may believe the host is on eth8 while PC is actually connected elsewhere; ARP/frames never reach the correct port.\n\n3) Host-side firewall/packet filtering or router-side forwarding filtering (less likely)\n   - If either host blocked ICMP or ARP, or if rp_filter/iptables on leaf prevented ARP discovery, ARP would fail; but leaf_router_0_0’s interface is up and other inter-router ARP entries exist, so the evidence points more strongly to L2 link/connectivity or mapping mismatch.\n\n4) Unexpected static blackhole route on the leaf (observed)\n   - leaf_router_0_0 shows a \"blackhole 10.0.0.0/30 proto static metric 20\" in its route listing. This is suspicious because a blackhole on an address range overlapping the host subnet could disrupt traffic to the .0/30 range; however:\n     - The blackhole covers 10.0.0.0/30 (which includes 10.0.0.0 - .3) — that includes host 10.0.0.2.\n     - This blackhole, if active/useful in the kernel route table, could cause local packets to be blackholed before ARP is resolved or could produce \"connect: Invalid argument\" from ping attempts seen in one command.\n     - The presence of this blackhole requires attention; it may be a misconfiguration that is directly affecting pc_0_0 reachability. It is a significant clue and could be the immediate reason the leaf is not properly resolving ARP for 10.0.0.2.\n   - Note: we saw both a connected route for 10.0.0.0/24 and also the blackhole for 10.0.0.0/30; the precedence/interaction requires kernel route table investigation (which route is installed in the FIB). The blackhole presence is abnormal and likely relevant.\n\nAdditional notes / supporting facts\n- BGP: FRR outputs show the /24s are present and next-hops are as expected on all routers; EBGP adjacency appears functional across spine/super-spine/leaf plane.\n- Many cross-pod pings succeeded in the reachability results, so the mid/fabric is functioning for most flows.\n- The failure is localized to the two hosts and their leaf edges — leaf-router visibility of the hosts is missing (lack of ARP) and leaf->host pings fail.\n\nSummary of likely scenario\n- The network control plane and the fabric are healthy. The observed mutual loss between pc_0_0 and pc_0_1 is caused by an edge-layer problem: either broken/misconnected host-to-leaf L2 links, host NIC namespace/mapping mismatch, or an explicit blackhole/static route on leaf_router_0_0 affecting addresses in 10.0.0.0/30 (which includes 10.0.0.2). The lack of an ARP entry on leaf_router_0_0 for 10.0.0.2 and the ping failures from the leaf to the host are the strongest indicators of an edge/L2 issue or local route blackholing.\n\nRecommended next investigative data (if further diagnosis required)\n- On leaf_router_0_0:\n  - show kernel/fib route for 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.0.2 (ip route get 10.0.0.2) to determine which route (blackhole or connected) is chosen by the kernel.\n  - arp/bridge/ethernet link statistics for the interface connected to the host (check which eth is the host-facing one, confirm link state).\n  - iptables / sysctl (rp_filter) settings.\n  - tcpdump/packet capture on the host-facing interface while initiating ARP from pc_0_0 to see if ARP requests reach the leaf and if ARP replies are seen.\n- On pc_0_0:\n  - verify ARP table, generate ARP (arping) towards gateway to observe L2 frames.\n  - check whether the PC interface is in the expected network namespace and that its link is actually connected to the leaf’s corresponding interface.\n- Confirm the origin and purpose of the \"blackhole 10.0.0.0/30\" route on leaf_router_0_0 and whether it is installed in the kernel FIB.\n\n(End of diagnostic report)\n\nNote: I have focused on detection, localization, and root-cause hypotheses. No remediation steps were performed or recommended in this report. If you want, I can run the targeted follow-up commands listed above and return their outputs to narrow the cause to one definite root cause.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 97771, "output_tokens": 5125, "total_tokens": 102896, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 96896}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2624}}}
